properties.documentation: Two integers that define the start and end positions of a range of residues, possibly with length zero, and specified using coordinates. [Source: VMC]

documentation.value: Base number of coordinate system (0 for 0-based numbering or coordinates, inclusive start, exclusive end, 1 for 1-based numbering, inclusive start, inclusive end) [Source: FHIR Guidance Document] A coordinate system is a specification for spatial location that uses a set of numbers, or coordinates, to uniquely determine the position of a point (based on Bioportal). [Source: Bioportal]

properties.documentation: A formatted sequence. The attached sequence can be processed using existing software tools designed for the given format.

The process of assembling many short DNA sequences together such that they represent the original chromosomes from which the DNA originated. [Source: Bioportal; https://bioportal.bioontology.org/ontologies/EDAM?p=classes&conceptid=http%3A%2F%2Fedamontology.org%2Foperation_0525 ]
The genome assembly is simply the genome sequence produced after chromosomes have been fragmented, those fragments have been sequenced, and the resulting sequences have been put back together. [Source: https://www.ensembl.org]

documentation.value: The Genome Build used for reference, following GRCh build versions e.g. 'GRCh 37' [Source: FHIR Guidance Document]

properties.documentation: A biological sequence entity characterized relative to some other biological sequence entity (typically a reference). [Source: MSO:0002072]

One or more molecular sequences, possibly with associated annotation. [ Source: Bioportal; https://bioportal.bioontology.org/ontologies/EDAM?p=classes&conceptid=http%3A%2F%2Fedamontology.org%2Fdata_2044 ]
A representation of a molecular sequence (although the sequence may not be biological in origin), including DNA, RNA, and protein. Sequences are represented using canonical directionality, such as 5’-to-3’ for nucleotide sequences and N-to-C for amino acid sequences.

documentation.value: Name(s) or title(s) of the sequence.

The type of sequence (e.g., genomic, plasmid, oligonucleotide, mRNA, tRNA, rRNA, ncRNA, protein, peptide)
A sequence provides information about any biopolymer sequences. Specialized subclasses are provided to denote specialized instances of sequences, such as "Codon Sequence", "Reference Sequence", "Protein Sequence", etc. Can be used to encode for the "sequencing-scope" pragma in GVF files. See subclasses for applications in both GFF3 and GVF files. [ Source: Bioportal; https://bioportal.bioontology.org/ontologies/GFVO?p=classes&conceptid=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.codamono.com%2Fbiointerchange%2Fgfvo%23Sequence ]

properties.documentation: Represents a single edit action (insert, delete or replace) on the occurrences of referenceAllele, within the referenceInterval of a referenced sequence, with replacementAllele.

documentation.value: Interval on a referenceSequence in which referenceAllele occurs.
Sequence of referenceAllele to be replaced by replacementAllele.
sequence of replacementAllele - used to replace the referenceAllele.

properties.documentation: This abstract class represents the many different ways a molecular sequence could be represented. It allows a single instance of Sequence to link to the many file formats (etc) that are available for that sequence.
An unformatted sequence represented as a simple string.

documentation.value: The coding system (alphabet) used by the sequence. While IUPAC symbols are frequently assumed, this attribute can denote whether an amino acid sequence is encoded as single letter or 3-letter abbreviations.

properties.documentation:
The period of time or the distance separating two instances, events, or occurrences. [Source: NCI Thesaurus; https://ncit.nci.nih.gov/ncitbrowser/ConceptReport.jsp?dictionary=NCI_Thesaurus&version=19.03d&ns=ncit&code=C25543&key=n1414369706&b=1&n=null ]
An interval is a set containing all points between two given points. An abstract class to define Sequence Interval.
